<h1>
  When Pathogens Leave <span>Genetic Footprints</span>
</h1>

<p class="hero-sub">
  An infectious disease genomics story about COVID-19, pathogen tracking,
  genomic surveillance, variant detection, and public-health response.
</p>

<div class="story-image">
  <img
    src="/pathogen-genomic-surveillance.png"
    alt="COVID-19 genomic surveillance illustration showing viral sequencing, variant tracking, and public-health response"
  >

  <p class="credit">
    Illustration: PanorOmics original visual concept for COVID-19 genomic surveillance and pathogen tracking.
  </p>

  <p class="image-explain">
    The image represents COVID-19 genomic surveillance, where viral sequencing helps track variants, monitor transmission patterns, and connect pathogen genomes to public-health action.
  </p>
</div>

<section class="section">

  <h2>
    The <span>Public-Health Story</span>
  </h2>

  <p>
    During an infectious disease outbreak, many cases may look similar from the outside.
    But inside each pathogen is genetic information that can reveal how it is changing,
    spreading, and moving through populations.
  </p>

  <p>
    COVID-19 showed the world how genomic surveillance can become a public-health tool.
    By sequencing viral genomes, scientists can identify variants, compare viral lineages,
    detect transmission patterns, and support decisions about testing, monitoring,
    vaccines, and outbreak response.
  </p>

</section>

<section class="section">

  <h2>
    Why <span>Genomics Matters</span>
  </h2>

  <p>
    Pathogens accumulate genetic changes over time. These changes can act like molecular
    footprints. When researchers compare viral sequences from different places and time
    points, they can reconstruct how variants emerge and how outbreaks may be connected.
  </p>

  <p>
    For SARS-CoV-2, genomic sequencing helped identify major variants and supported
    global surveillance efforts. This did not replace epidemiology, clinical testing,
    or public-health investigation. Instead, genomics added another layer of evidence
    to help scientists understand the outbreak more precisely.
  </p>

</section>

<section class="section">

  <h2>
    The Omics <span>Connection</span>
  </h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Genomics:</strong> reads pathogen genomes to identify mutations, variants, and lineages.</li>
    <li><strong>Transcriptomics:</strong> can help study host and pathogen gene activity during infection.</li>
    <li><strong>Proteomics:</strong> connects viral proteins with immune recognition, diagnostics, and vaccine research.</li>
    <li><strong>Metabolomics:</strong> can reveal biochemical changes associated with infection and immune response.</li>
    <li><strong>Public-health data:</strong> connects molecular signals with geography, timing, transmission, and intervention.</li>
  </ul>

</section>

<section class="section">

  <h2>
    What This Story <span>Teaches</span>
  </h2>

  <p>
    Genomic surveillance shows that infectious disease control is not only about counting
    cases. It is also about reading molecular change. A pathogen genome can help reveal
    where an outbreak may be moving, whether a variant is emerging, and how public-health
    systems can respond faster.
  </p>

  <p>
    The larger lesson is simple: pathogens leave genetic footprints. Omics sciences help
    scientists read those footprints and connect molecular data to human health,
    community protection, and public-health action.
  </p>

</section>

